(747, 'event', '168', 'comment', 'FR', '<p>Le stick du sous-lieutenant Gayard est parachut√© dans la nuit du 14 au 15  ao√ªt sur le terrain \"Heliotrope\" situ√© au col de Casse-Froide √† six kilom√®tres au  sud-est de Beaujeu.</p>', 'David Portier', '2012-06-25 19:41:03'),
(748, 'event', '169', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>During the¬† night of 14 to 15 August¬† Aspirant Barres and his stick were parachuted into a field situated by the col Casse-Froide six kilometres south east of Beaujeu.</p>', 'paul golder', '2012-09-19 03:02:17'),
(749, 'event', '169', 'comment', 'FR', '<p>Le stick de l\'aspirant Barres est parachut√© dans la nuit du 14 au 15  ao√ªt sur un terrain situ√© au col de Casse-Froide √† six kilom√®tres au  sud-est de Beaujeu.</p>', 'David Portier', '2012-05-18 13:54:12'),
(750, 'event', '170', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>Apr√®s un premier voyage dans la nuit du 14 ao√ªt, le stick du sous-lieutenant Ferchaud est parachut√© dans la nuit du 15 au 16 ao√ªt sur le terrain \"Vinaigrette\" sur la commune de Larajasse, entre Saint-Symphorien et Sainte-Catherine.</p>\r\n<p>Dans la nuit du 18 ao√ªt, le stick et un groupe de maquisards sabotent la voie ferr√©e au niveau de la garde de l\'Arbresle. La station de pompage est √©galement d√©truite ainsi qu\'un important mat√©riel.</p>\r\n<p>Le 22 ao√ªt, le S/Lt Ferchaud et ses hommes attaquent un d√©p√¥t de carburant √† Pierre-B√©nite.</p>\r\n<p>Le stick est particuli√®rement actif et monte de nombreuses embuscades entre Roanne et Lyon.</p>\r\n<p>Le 3 septembre, les SAS font leur entr√©e dans Lyon et participent au nettoyage de la ville. Le 12 septembre, le S/Lt Ferchaud se voit remettre une d√©coration par le g√©n√©ral de Lattre.</p>', 'David Portier', '2012-06-25 19:53:47'),
(751, 'event', '171', 'comment', 'EN', ' Dropped near Saint Martin la Plaine nord de Rive de Gier', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(752, 'event', '172', 'comment', 'EN', '', 'David Portier', '2012-05-18 13:21:43'),
(753, 'event', '173', 'comment', 'EN', 'As the situation in Brittany became complex a reconnaissance mission was dispatched to contact Bourgoin and D√©plante and to ensure an officer returned to England to report back.  Major Cary-Elwes supported by a small team of parachutists was sent to make contact and captain Leblond reported back.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(754, 'event', '177', 'comment', 'EN', ' In these two zones the enemy were remaining in their garisons and did not present particularly conventint targets for SAS action.  There was also no major objective to impede movement nor the arrival of reinforcements.  The two missions supported by resistance  attacked garrisons at Egleton (Snelgrove) and Bourganeuf (Marshall).  The 24 th August they regrouped and turned thier attention to the retreating enemy forces at Charteauroux.  Operating from the forest of Chataueroux supported by resistance and aviation they harrased the retreating enemy who surrenderd  at Issoudoun on the 10th September.  The 14th September the two missions joined operation Moses at the enemy pocket of Saint Nazaire.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(755, 'event', '178', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>*</p>', 'paul golder', '2013-12-18 17:06:25'),
(756, 'event', '179', 'comment', 'EN', ' dropped 2/8/1944', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(757, 'event', '180', 'comment', 'EN', ' landed at bonbon 6/8/1944', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(758, 'event', '181', 'comment', 'EN', ' dropped 7/8/1944', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(759, 'event', '182', 'comment', 'EN', ' landed at Bonbon 9/8/1944', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(760, 'event', '183', 'comment', 'EN', ' dropped 14/8/44', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(761, 'event', '184', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>The group was landed by Dakota on the dropping zone \"Bonbon\" in the night of¬† 27 to 28 August. The SAS carried out several strikes towards the the forest of Mareuil and Chauvigny.¬† At the beginning of September aspirant Levi and his men met up with lieutenant Leblond (Samson) at Le Blanc. The detachment operated in the direction of Chateauroux, La Chatre and then Limoges before rejoining the pocket of Saint-Nazaire.</p>', 'paul golder', '2011-01-31 09:58:55'),
(762, 'event', '185', 'comment', 'EN', ' Overland reinforcement of the Dickens, Moses and Harrod missions', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(763, 'event', '210', 'comment', 'EN', ' Led by Lt Rousseau of 2SAS this sabotage mission operated in the Vosges.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(764, 'event', '211', 'comment', 'EN', ' Members of 3 and 4 SAS also participated in actions with 1 & 2 SAS and with sticks from the Belgium SAS (5SAS).  Often this was to provide support with local knowledge or of course language skills.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(765, 'event', '213', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>Bourgoin was asked to provide a detachment of troups to escort Intelligence officers into Paris as it was being liberated.  Apart from protection they were required to help liberate Gestapo prisons and to help in the arrest of collaborators and spies.  Beteze was assigned the task and took a number of jeeps and about 20 men with him.  They thus had the honour of arriving with the liberating forces and parading down the Champs Elysees.  Itturia and his jeep were assigned to the detachment but were ambushed immediately before setting out from Vannes</p>', 'paul golder', '2013-12-10 09:55:41'),
(766, 'event', '214', 'comment', 'EN', ' A sabotage 2nd mission, commanded by Captain Scott, against communication routes between the Moselle and Rhin.  Lt Grumbach particiapated in one of the eight sticks dropped. ', 'David Portier', '2006-05-22 11:51:59'),
(767, 'event', '215', 'comment', 'EN', 'Teams of radio operators were dropped near Pesquen as reinforcements for those in the field.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(768, 'event', '216', 'comment', 'EN', ' To impede the retreat of the enemy by destroying railway connections and bridges and harrassing the enemy along their route. After 14th September they continued supporting the mission Dickens in Loire Altlantic and then at La Rochelle.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(769, 'event', '220', 'comment', 'FR', 'Tout se d√©roule bien pour les √©quipes Pierre 3 et Pierre 4 qui sont parachut√©es √†  l\'endroit pr√©vu, pr√®s de Locarn √†  deux ou trois kilom√®tres de la for√™t de Duault. <br /><br />Les hommes se regroupent rapidement puis prennent un peu de repos dans les fourr√©s le temps que les deux officiers, les lieutenant Botella et Deschamps, fassent le point. Quelques minutes plus tard, ils se mettent en route vers la lisi√®re des bois de Duault. Apr√®s environ une heure de marche, au lever du jour le matin du 6 juin, les SAS installent leur campement et Andr√© Botella prend contact par radio avec le Quartier G√©n√©ral √†  Londres.<br /><br />Au matin, le groupe entre en contact avec deux patriotes membres de la compagnie FTP \" Tito \" de Ma√´l-Pestivien. Aussit√¥t, les deux maquisards partent pr√©venir l\'Etat-major FFI des C√¥tes-du-Nord qui est rassembl√© √†  Peumerit-Quintin. <br />Peu √†  peu, les r√©sistants affluent √†  la base Samwest. Les parachutistes pr√©parent alors une dropping-zone pour accueillir les renforts et ils demandent des parachutages d\'armes et de mat√©riel.<br />', 'david', '2009-01-21 18:39:44'),
(770, 'event', '120', 'comment', 'FR', '<p>Mission du 4th SAS</p>\r\n<p>Effectifs engag√©s: 56 hommes</p>\r\n<p>¬†</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Dans la nuit du 7 au 8 juin, dix-huit petites √©quipes de sabotage de 3 √†  5 hommes sont largu√©es √†  travers l\'ensemble de la Bretagne afin de r√©aliser des actions de sabotage bien d√©finies, principalement contre les moyens de communication de l\'ennemi.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Ces √©quipes sont largu√©es \"blind\", c\'est √†  dire sans comit√© de r√©ception, et elles ont re√ßu l\'ordre de ne pas prendre contact avec la population civile. Chaque groupe doit effectuer une mission principale qui est jug√©e prioritaire et qui consiste g√©n√©ralement √†  saboter la voie ferr√©e Brest-Paris. Les SAS doivent r√©aliser ensuite diff√©rentes missions secondaires (couper les lignes souterraines et les lignes t√©l√©phoniques, abattre les pyl√¥nes √†  haute tension) pour cr√©er le maximum de chaos dans les lignes ennemies et emp√™cher que les unit√©s allemandes stationn√©es en Bretagne ne rejoignent la Normandie.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Les diff√©rentes √©quipes ont dix jours pour op√©rer dans le secteur qui leur a √©t√© attribu√© puis elles doivent ensuite rejoindre les bases Dingson ou Samwest afin de prendre un peu de repos et se r√©armer.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A la suite de la dispersion de la base Samwest, les √©quipes re√ßoivent par radio l\'ordre de rejoindre la base sud. En fait, plusieurs groupes restent alors dans leur secteur o√π ils encadrent des patriotes et poursuivent les actions de sabotage.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Depuis l\'a√©rodrome de Brize-Norton, les bombardiers Armstrong Whitworth AW.41 \"Albemarle\" des 295th, 296th, 297th et 570th Squadron du 38th Group transportent chacun deux Parties vers leur zone d\'op√©ration.</p>\r\n<p>¬†</p>', 'David Portier', '2012-12-06 19:50:57'),
(771, 'event', '225', 'comment', 'EN', 'Squadron 1 arrived at Briare on the 30st August and immediately made contact with the enemy.  Captain Larralde requested reinforcements and  the 3rd company arrived however counter attacks by Varnier and Lesecq had already remedied the situation.  Squadron 1 reamined in the region of Briare eliminating the enemy in the area and helping in the liberation of Bourges.', '*', '2003-05-06 08:58:23'),
(772, 'event', '226', 'comment', 'EN', 'The second squadron was sent to patrol the left bank of the Loire in the direction of Nevers.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(773, 'event', '227', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>The third squadron of captain Puech-Samson arrived on the Loire the 31 August ans established itself in the region of Gien.</p>\r\n<p>Patrols operated towards Ch√¢teauroux, Isoudun¬† and Vierzon.¬† A large convoy was attacked on the 6th September near Neuvy-Pailloux.¬† At Mareuil, the patrols of aspirant Fauquet and S/Lt Nicol attacked and destroyed vehicles carrying the German headquarters staff of Bairritz.</p>\r\n<p>The following days the 3rd¬† squadron made an impressive penetration into the enemy held territory, in the south east direction of Angoul√™me, Saints Cognac and eventually P√©rigueux and Bordeaux where the jeeps regrouped on the 13 September.</p>', 'paul golder', '2012-09-19 02:58:12'),
(774, 'event', '228', 'comment', 'EN', 'Direction Nevers<br />', 'david', '2008-03-13 18:26:30'),
(775, 'event', '228', 'comment', 'FR', 'Ce squadron vient d\'√™tre form√© √†  Vannes par le capitaine D√©plante et regroupe en grande partie de nombreux jeunes maquisards bretons. <br />Les premiers √©l√©ments du 4√®me squadron atteignent Briare le 5 septembre et patrouillent dans le secteur de Nevers. <br />De retour de Paris, le lieutenant Betb√®ze et ses hommes sont charg√©s le 10 septembre de prendre contact √†  Autun avec les √©l√©ments de reconnaissance de la 1√®re Arm√©e fran√ßaise du g√©n√©ral de Lattre. Dans le m√™me temps, les sous-lieutenants de Camaret et Cochin et les √©l√©ments du 4√®me squadron poursuivent les op√©rations de harc√®lement entre Saint-Amand, Sancoins, Saint-Pierre-le-Moutiers et Decize.<br /><br />Dans la soir√©e du 11 septembre, les jeeps du capitaine D√©plante tournent autour du village de Saint-Pierre-le-Moutiers afin de pr√™ter main forte au peloton Le Bobinec du 2e squadron. Les parachutistes font croire √†  un important d√©tachement de reconnaissance alli√©. Apr√®s n√©gociation, le capitaine D√©plante obtient la reddition de pr√®s de 2.500 soldats allemands qui sont alors dirig√©s vers Moulins et Nevers.<br />', 'david', '2008-03-13 18:26:30'),
(776, 'event', '229', 'comment', 'EN', 'A reconnaissance mission by Lt Gabaudan on the 26th August reported that the enemy were well, established in the region around Pouiily sur Loire.  On the 29th August Bourgoin sent three companies to Briare where they were to establish a base.  A fourth company which had just been created was to follow as a headquaters company which had first to repair the remaining vehicles.\r\n\r\nThe enemy forces appeared to be guarding the bridges essential for any retreat from the south west to the north east.\r\n\r\nThe objective was to provide a mobile unit harrasing the enemy retreating from the South West to the North East of France. \r\n\r\n(the reports do not enable a complete distribution of men across the four Squadrons.)\r\n\r\nThus 54 jeeps each with 4 SAS together with a number of trailers and lorries left Vannes and set of  for the Loire.  This comprised all 4 SAS and some resistants who had joined them.  Betbeze led the 4SAS to Briare where the HQ was established.\r\n\r\n A total of 38 officers and 279 men were involved', '*', '2003-05-06 08:56:21'),
(777, 'event', '230', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>Apr√®s √™tre parvenu √† √©chapper √† l\'encerclement de Falaise, les unit√©s allemandes tentent de franchir la Seine.</p>\r\n<p>Diff√©rents √©l√©ments de la Brigade SAS re√ßoivent pour mission d\'effectuer des missions de sabotage, harc√®lement et renseignement en Normandie dans le secteur d\'Elbeuf.</p>\r\n<p>Ainsi, la mission est confi√©e √† 5 hommes du 1st SAS - 39 hommes du 2nd SAS - 60 hommes du 5th SAS qui sont parachut√©s les nuits des 16 et 17 ao√ªt dans des conditions difficiles et souvent dans des zones √©loign√©es des DZ pr√©vues.</p>\r\n<p>Ainsi, dans la nuit du 17 au 18 ao√ªt, cinq sticks aux ordres du Captain Holland (Trueform I - 11 hommes), du Captain Baillie (Trueform IV - 11 hommes), du Lt Samarine (Trueform II - 11 hommes), du Sgt Thorpe (Trueform - 10 hommes) et du Cpl Burton (Trueform V) sont parachut√©s en Normandie.</p>', 'David Portier', '2018-04-26 06:29:23'),
(778, 'person', '674', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>Born in Demangevelle (70<br /> on 22 May 1917..</p>', 'george', '2018-09-10 20:16:24'),
(779, 'event', '270', 'comment', 'EN', ' Complete records of the disposition of all Frankilin members are not available so those non allocated are listed here.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(780, 'event', '271', 'comment', 'EN', 'As the autumn turned to winter, the Germans were fighting a slow rearguard action and the war in Europe was still not settled.  A surprised awaited the Americans in the Ardennes as on the 16th December the Germans under Von Rundstedt made a major offensive.<br /><br />The allies decided to commit the French SAS to the support of the Americans.  They were near by at Montmirail and entry by air was impossible so an overland insertion was required.  4SAS  had 40 jeeps resulting from the Spencer operations on the Loire.  The squadron, left Montmirail on the 24 December for Bertrix and St Hubert in the Belgian Ardennes.     <br />The weather was foul and the SAS held their position in the front for a month until 25th January 1945.  On the 25th the SAS were recalled to Bertrix, their base for the operations in the Ardennes.  The 29th saw them back in Montmirail and by the end of the month they were in Bases in East Anglia awaiting further action.', 'david', '2008-03-13 19:39:35'),
(781, 'event', '272', 'comment', 'EN', ' It was only 9 days after returning from the Ardennes that the SAS were on the move again.  Starting the 9th of February they transferred From their base in Montmirail to Le Havre and by the 17th they were bound for England.\r\nThe allies standard technique for driving forward against the enemy was to lay down a heavy artillery and air bombardment prior to the arrival of the allied tanks.  However Queen Wilhelmine had requested that the allies should make an effort to spare the dykes and drainage systems.  Thus Calvert, commander of the SAS, proposed that the French battalions should be used to precede the Canadians advancing to Groningen.  They were to seize some bridges and destroy others thus enabling the rapid advance of the Canadians.\r\n\r\nThe plan was to drop 23 sticks of 2RCP and 24 sticks of 3RCP from Stirlings together with 18 jeeps from Halifaxs.   The intention was to drop them on the 6-7th April and they were to either meet at the airport of Steenwijk if the allies had arrived or else regroup at Coeverden.  The Canadians should arrive within 72 hours.  The SAS were required to return ASAP to England with a view to future missions.\r\n\r\nThe operation was not low key, with announcements by radio, a supporting airforce action and the dropping of a number of dummies all to give the illusion of a larger operation.\r\n\r\nThe operation was eventually scheduled for the night of the 7-8 April.  It was not until 17th of April that the last men flew back to Britain, the operation intended to last 3 days lasted 10.\r\n', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(782, 'event', '273', 'comment', 'EN', 'The French SAS received parachute training during 1942-1943 from the Polish airforce at Largo in Scotland.  The lists of parachutes brevete includes non SAS Free French.', '*', '2003-03-27 09:05:43'),
(783, 'event', '293', 'comment', 'EN', 'The French CIA arrived in North Africa in Janary 1942 and were to support the liberation of North Africa fighting alomgside the Britich SAS until January 1943.', '*', '2003-04-10 04:52:11'),
(784, 'event', '294', 'comment', 'EN', ' Operating in Libya behind the Axis front at El Alamein, the objectives were to destroy enemy planes on the ground, harrasing enemy convoys and destroying lines of communications.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(785, 'event', '299', 'comment', 'EN', 'A French SAS team, accompanied by Lord Jellico (BR) and Lt Petrakis (Greek). was tranfered by submarine leaving Alexandria on the 7 th June 1942.   The objective of the mission was to attack the airfield of Heraklion, to sabotage planes, installations, munitions and fuel.    \r\n\r\nHaving achieved the sabotage the SAS were found by the enemy.  Leostic was killed the other French SAS captured..  Thery were transfered to prison camps in Germany. ', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(786, 'event', '300', 'comment', 'EN', 'Operation Snowdrop was launched to gain control of the port of Benghasi and destroy enemy shipping in the port. Leaving Kabrit on 15th August 1942 the SAS esatblished a base at Koufra from which an attach on Benghasi was launched. The LRDG was simultaneaously attaking Barce and Tobruk. The force was detected and came under air attack. The mission was aborted, many SAS wounded and killed, much equipment destroyed.\r\n', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(787, 'event', '302', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>This mission was betrayed and all participants captured except Jordan. Many of the prisoners were to die when the boat, the Nino Bixio which was transfering them to Italy, was sunk.</p>', 'David Portier', '2018-06-26 10:49:20'),
(788, 'event', '307', 'comment', 'EN', 'On the 8th November the Allies, American and British, launched an invasion from the west with landings in Algeria and Marocco. Rommel\'s days in North Africa were numbered, however he was under orders to resist at all cost.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(789, 'event', '308', 'comment', 'EN', ' On arrival in Egypt the Company was sent to  Kabrit on the Suez canal where the British SAS Brigade under Stirling had their base.  Over the next year many voluntiers were to arrive at Kabrit from various parts of the French Empire.  ', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(790, 'event', '309', 'comment', 'EN', ' The operation was to  attack the road and rail links between Aghelia and Tripoli.  The operation was carried out with mainly new troups and resulted in heavy losses to B Squadron. We do not have details of the French Squadron complement to B Squadrons actions apart from it being led by Lt Martin so all remaining FF have been allocated here.  ', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(791, 'event', '310', 'comment', 'EN', ' The aim of the mission was to impede enemy airfields from attacking supply convoys trying to reach Malta.  Seven airfields behind the enemy front at Tobruk were to be targeted by the SAS supported by the LRDG at the same time a group would attack the enemy base of Herakilion on the island of Crete.  This SAS group was to be carried to Crete by submarine from Alexandria. ', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(792, 'event', '312', 'comment', 'EN', '*', '*', '2003-05-16 04:29:22'),
(793, 'event', '312', 'comment', 'FR', '<p align=justify>Suite √†¬† la demande du g√©n√©ral de Gaulle, il est d√©cid√© que les parachutistes fran√ßais doivent √™tre rassembl√©s en Grande-Bretagne afin de se pr√©parer pour les op√©rations de Lib√©ration en Europe. \r\n<br>Le 10 d√©cembre 1942, une vingtaine d\'hommes de la 1√®re CCP embarque √†¬† Suez sous le commandement du capitaine Christian Fouchet, assist√© des S/Lts Mairet et Jacquier. Le capitaine Jean Lambert, hospitalis√© au Caire, doit rejoindre plus tard.', 'David Portier', '2006-03-09 15:15:05'),
(794, 'event', '315', 'comment', 'EN', ' A small group led by Jordan and Martin remained to see the completion of the war in North Africa.  The Battalion members who remained in North Africa continued their sabotage and harrasment of the enemy comunication lines from Sousse to Gabes.\r\n\r\nFour French patrols were operating together with patrols form the British SAS  Three patrols led by Jordan were to operate on the east of the Tunisia coast.  The fourth patrol led by Martin under Striling was to reach ourt westwards towards the approaching American 1st army.  The result was rather bad for the SAS with 15 of th 40 men being captured, including Stirling and Jordan.\r\n\r\nThose not captured were eventually reunited in Constantine 7/2/1943 ', '*', '2003-05-16 04:33:59'),
(795, 'event', '316', 'comment', 'EN', ' The patrol arrived at Constantine 7/2/1943.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(796, 'event', '317', 'comment', 'EN', ' The Jordan patrol was captured on the 28/1/1943 at Djedel Bou-Hadma. ', '*', '2003-05-19 07:29:50'),
(797, 'event', '318', 'comment', 'EN', 'The patrol had two jeeps made contact with the 1st US army 30/1/1943 at the Djebel Orbata', '*', '2003-05-19 07:31:09'),
(798, 'event', '319', 'comment', 'EN', 'Having lost both their jeeps the patrol finished the mission on foot arriving at Zennouch station on 30/1/1943 to be met by the 1st US army.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(799, 'event', '121', 'comment', 'FR', '<p>Parachut√© pr√®s de Plouagat, le groupe sabote la voie ferr√©e Saint-Brieuc - Guingamp pr√®s de Ch√¢telaudren. Suite au d√©raillement d\'un train, la ligne est rendue inutilisable.</p>\r\n<p>La Party 401 prend alors contact avec la r√©sistance et s\'installe pr√®s de Saint-Fiacre. Fin, juin, les trois hommes retrouvent le SAS Ren√© Siccardi, rescap√© de la base Samwest, et ensemble, ils rejoignent le secteur de Loud√©ac puis de Merdrignac.</p>\r\n<p>D√©but ao√ªt, les hommes participent au combat pour la lib√©ration de Merdrignac et la r√©gion.</p>', 'David Portier', '2012-10-21 17:12:28'),
(800, 'event', '340', 'comment', 'EN', ' Jedburgh Frederick was assigned to the Duault base and later worked with Smith (Wash) and Deplante (Grog) near Peumerit-Quintin.', 'David Portier', '2005-10-15 06:25:13'),
(801, 'event', '343', 'comment', 'EN', 'Fin juillet, un premier d√©tachement pr√©curseur compos√© de l\'√©quipe Jedburgh Ronald et de quelques S.A.S. fran√ßais dont Andr√© Soup√©, est parachut√© pr√®s de Kerien. Ces hommes doivent armer et encadrer les maquisards mais √©galement pr√©parer la r√©ception de l\'Etat-major FFI. <br />Dans la nuit du 4 ao√ªt, le colonel Eon et son Etat-major sont largu√©s en compagnie du colonel Passy et de divers √©l√©ments du BCRA et de l\'Intelligence Service. Ils sont accompagn√©s √©galement par quelques parachutistes SAS dont le major Cary-Elwes et l\'√©quipe radio dirig√©e par le Sgt Delplanque.<br />', 'david', '2009-01-17 20:55:42'),
